<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - ROCKWELL TANDEM AXLE FORWARD REAR DRIVE UNITS -
        DISASSEMBLE
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>DISASSEMBLE</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="6">
            <title>OUTPUT SHAFT AND OUTPUT BEARING CAGE ASSEMBLY</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Pry under the flange of the oil seal to remove the oil seal from the output bearing
                    cage. Replace with new oil seal when assembling (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1401136">Figure 36</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1401136" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg14/g1401136.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 36. Remove Oil Seal From Output Bearing Cage</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. OUTPUT SHAFT</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. BEARING ASSEMBLIES</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. SNAP RING</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. OUTPUT YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. OIL SEAL</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. SPACER</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If either the bearing cup or the cone must be removed, both the cup and the cone must be
                        replaced as a matched set.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the external snap ring (yoke-to-cone spacer) from the through shaft.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the internal snap ring that holds the bearing cup in the output cage (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1401137">Figure 37</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1401137" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg14/g1401137.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 37. Remove Internal Snap Ring</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. BEARING CAGE</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. SNAP RING</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. OUTPUT SHAFT</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. END VIEW</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If necessary, remove the output shaft and the bearing cones as an assembly from the
                    output bearing cage.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <warning>
                        <para>Observe all warnings and cautions concerning press operation to avoid serious personal
                            injury and possible damage to components.
                        </para>
                    </warning>
                </specpara>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Put the output shaft and the output bearing cage in a press (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1401138">Figure 38</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1401138" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../figg14/g1401138.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 38. Put Output Shaft and Output Bearing Cage in Press</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>When the output shaft is pressed from the cage, the inner cup remains in the cage. The
                                outer cup is removed with the output shaft and the cones.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Press the output shaft and cones from the bearing cage.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove the outer cup from the output shaft.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a press or a bearing puller to remove the bearing cones from the output shaft.
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <title>Press Method</title>
                    </para>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Put a used bearing cup on the inner bearing cone.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Put the output shaft in a press as shown in
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f1401139">Figure 39</hotlnk>. The used bearing cup supports the through
                            shaft.
                        </para>
                        <figure id="f1401139" figsize="col-wide">
                            <graphic filename="../figg14/g1401139.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                     resolution="72"/>
                            <caption>Figure 39. Put Output Shaft in Press</caption>
                        </figure>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Press the output shaft through at the bearing cones. Discard the bearing cones.</para>
                    </step3>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <title>Bearing Puller Method</title>
                    </para>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Put a used bearing cup on the inner bearing cone.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Install a bearing puller tool on the output shaft as shown in
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f1401140">Figure 40</hotlnk>. The bearing cup supports the output shaft.
                        </para>
                        <figure id="f1401140" figsize="col-wide">
                            <graphic filename="../figg14/g1401140.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                     resolution="72"/>
                            <caption>Figure 40. Install Bearing Puller Tool on Output Shaft</caption>
                        </figure>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Pull the bearing cones off the output shaft. Discard the bearing cones.</para>
                    </step3>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If necessary, use a brass drift and a hammer to carefully tap the inner cup from the
                    cage. Discard the cup (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1401141">Figure 41</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1401141" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg14/g1401141.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 41. Carefully Tap Inner Cup From Cage</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
